In the `game.js` file, you should already have a `movePlayer` function that handles the player's movement based on the arrow keys. Here is the implementation of the `movePlayer` function:
```javascript
function movePlayer(dx, dy) {
  const newX = player.x + dx;
  const newY = player.y + dy;

  if (isInBounds(newX, newY) && !isCellOccupiedByBot(newX, newY) && !isCellOccupiedByObject(newX, newY)) {
    board[player.y][player.x].classList.remove('player');
    player.x = newX;
    player.y = newY;
    board[player.y][player.x].classList.add('player');

    checkForPackageCollision();
    checkForTargetCollision();
  }
}
```
This function takes two arguments, `dx` and `dy`, which represent the change in the player's x and y coordinates, respectively. The function first calculates the new x and y coordinates by adding `dx` and `dy` to the player's current position. Then, it checks if the new position is within the board boundaries, not occupied by a bot, and not occupied by an object. If all these conditions are met, the player is moved to the new position, and the function checks for collisions with the package and the target.

The mobile controls in my previous response use the `movePlayer` function to control the player's movement when the corresponding buttons are clicked.

To make the game screen responsive and adapt to mobile devices, you can use CSS media queries and update the existing styles. Follow these steps:

1. Update the CSS file (styles.css) to add media queries for smaller screens:
```css
/* Add the following to your existing styles.css file */

@media screen and (max-width: 600px) {
  body {
    font-size: 14px;
  }

  #game-container {
    max-width: 100%;
  }

  #board {
    max-width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    font-size: 1.5em;
  }

  #game-controls {
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
  }

  #game-info {
    font-size: 1.2em;
  }

  #difficulty-control {
    margin: 10px 0;
  }

  #mobile-controls {
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }

  #mobile-controls button {
    width: 40px;
    height: 40px;
  }
}
```
This media query targets screens with a maximum width of 600px (which should cover most mobile devices). The styles within this media query will only apply when the screen size meets this condition.

Here's a breakdown of the changes made for mobile devices:

* The base font size is reduced to 14px.
* The game container and board elements are set to have a maximum width of 100%.
* The board height is set to auto, and the font size is increased to 1.5em for better visibility.
* The game controls are displayed in a column layout with center alignment.
* The difficulty control and mobile controls have adjusted margins.
* The mobile control buttons have increased width and height for easier interaction.

These changes should make the game screen adapt better to mobile devices and improve usability. You can further adjust the styles and breakpoints as needed to better suit your target devices.

To disable other keyboard, mouse, and touch input during the game, you can use event listeners that capture and prevent the default behavior of these events. Follow these steps:

1. Update the JavaScript file (game.js) to add event listeners that prevent the default behavior:
```javascript
// Add the following code at the bottom of the game.js file

function disableEvent(event) {
  event.preventDefault();
}

document.addEventListener('keydown', (event) => {
  // Allow arrow keys and space for game control
  if (![32, 37, 38, 39, 40].includes(event.keyCode)) {
    disableEvent(event);
  }
});

document.addEventListener('mousedown', disableEvent);
document.addEventListener('mousemove', disableEvent);
document.addEventListener('mouseup', disableEvent);

document.addEventListener('touchstart', disableEvent);
document.addEventListener('touchmove', disableEvent);
document.addEventListener('touchend', disableEvent);
```
This code adds event listeners for the keyboard, mouse, and touch events. The `disableEvent` function is used to prevent the default behavior of these events.

For the `keydown` event, it checks if the event's `keyCode` is not one of the allowed keys (32 for space, 37 for left arrow, 38 for up arrow, 39 for right arrow, and 40 for down arrow). If the key code is not in the allowed list, the event is disabled.

The `mousedown`, `mousemove`, and `mouseup` events are disabled for the mouse, and the `touchstart`, `touchmove`, and `touchend` events are disabled for touch input.

These changes should prevent other keyboard, mouse, and touch input during the game, ensuring that only the allowed controls can be used.
